    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-08-14T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-08-14T14:00:00-05:00" n="581"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d581">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 656.119/690</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-08-14T20:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 14, 1918, 8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received August 15, 2.50 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1106. War Trade Board [from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1"
                        >Sheldon</persName>]:</p>
                <p>No. 1266. Your 1030, Department’s 754, August 13. I fear you had not considered
                    the last part of my 1197, Embassy’s 965, August 9, 6 p.m.,<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d581fn1">Not printed.</note> when you despatched your 1030. I will
                    again point out to the Foreign Office that the manner in which they reopened
                    negotiations on Oppenheimer’s return was strongly objected to by our Government.
                    I very much doubt if complaint is justified at their manner of handling any
                    negotiations during the last few weeks; on the other point of the advisability
                    of making an offer of <hi rend="italic">modus vivendi</hi> rations, this I think
                    is clearly a difference of opinion and as <pb facs="0688" n="1522"
                        xml:id="pg_1522"/> we have received several indications that the Dutch
                    propose recommencing negotiations, it would appear that this could be traced to
                    the necessity of coming to terms which would not have come to pass, at least in
                    the opinion of <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_TSWB1">Townley</persName>
                    and the Foreign Office, had <hi rend="italic">modus vivendi</hi> rations been
                    granted. <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_TAE1">Taylor</persName> seems to
                    have felt the force of the British attitude and will shortly explain the
                    situation to you in detail.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
